answer_choices18[0]="<p>Connect with disabled students enrolled in your courses and ask them about their preferred instructional/learning strategies.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>";
answer_choices18[1]="<p>Regarding course materials, consider colors, fonts, and formats that are easily viewed by students with low vision or a form of color blindness and avoid using websites that have several flash-based visuals that may cause seizure.</p>";
answer_choices18[2]="<p>Post course materials, assignments, and deadlines with advanced notice because it allows students time to plan for accommodations and workload.</p>";
answer_choices18[3]="<p>Use multiple formats for instruction for delivering content because students learn different ways. You can make outlines or recordings available online or explain in a video all printed assignments.</p>";
answer_choices18[4]="<p>Prepare alternative assignments because some students may have difficulties with the requested method of delivery such as presentation and public speaking.</p>";
answer_choices18[5]="<p>Think of multiple ways students may be able to participate without feeling excluded instead of assuming what activities they can or cannot do.</p>";
answer_choices18[6]="<p>Remove negative portrayals of the members of the disabled population.</p>";
answer_choices18[7]="<p>Encourage students to hide their disabilities at Student Disability Services.</p>";
answer_choices18[8]="<p>Make disabled students feel like any other student by using positive reinforcement and giving them personalized attention during the learning process.</p>";
answer_choices18[9]="<p>Follow universal design principles and create assessments that offer options for demonstrating relevant knowledge and skills. Let students choose the method to deliver their representative project.</p>";
